nuse" rel=3D"noopener"><strong>hypotenuse</strong></a> (<strong>c</strong> =
=E2=80=93 longest side) in a right triangle. For the calculation, you just =
have to enter the lengths of the <strong>two legs</strong> (<strong>a and b=
</strong> =E2=80=93 perpendicular sides) and click on calculate. The result=
 will be displayed automatically.</p>
<blockquote><p>The Pythagorean theorem is a fundamental formula in geometry=
 that applies to right triangles, that is, triangles that have a 90=C2=B0 a=
ngle (right angle).</p></blockquote>
<h3><strong>What is the pythagorean theorem?</strong></h3>
<p>The <strong>Pythagoras=E2=80=99 theorem</strong> states that in a right =
triangle, the sum of the squares of the legs (sides that form the right ang=
le) is equal to the square of the hypotenuse (side opposite the right angle=
 and longest). The <strong>Pythagoras equation</strong>&nbsp;is: <strong>a=
=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2 </strong>(a and b are legs, and c is the hypot=
enuse)</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Legs</strong>: The two sides that form the right angle (perpend=
icular sides)</li>
<li><strong>Hypotenuse</strong>: The side opposite the right angle (longest=
 side)</li>
<li><strong>Right triangle</strong>: The Pythagorean equation only applies =
to triangles that have a 90-degree angle.</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>How to calculate the Pythagorean theorem?</strong></h3>
<p>To apply <strong>Pythagoras rule</strong> and <strong>calculate the hypo=
tenuse </strong>(c) of a right triangle. The forluma is: <strong>a=C2=B2 + =
b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2</strong>. Then, from the Pythagorean equation, we can e=
xtract that <strong>c =3D =E2=88=9A(a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2)</strong>, where <str=
ong>a and b are the legs</strong> that form the right angle.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_47568" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-4756=
