<p>With all these formulas, you have the mathematical foundation to perform=
 calculations in <strong>geometric applications</strong> or a useful <stron=
g>hypotenuse and legs calculator</strong>.</p>
<p>Some calculations of <strong>Pythagorean theorem examples</strong>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Exercise 1</strong>. Imagine you have a right triangle where on=
e leg measures 3 centimeters and the other measures 4 centimeters=E2=80=A6 =
What would be the value of the hypotenuse, the longest side? We could do th=
e following calculations:
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;">
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Square of the first leg: 3=C3=973 =3D 9 cm (Value leg a)</li>
<li>Square of the second leg: 4=C3=974 =3D 16 cm (Value leg b)</li>
<li>Now, we add those results: 9+16 =3D 25 cm (Value of hypotenuse)</li>
<li>If we apply the <strong>Pythagorean law</strong>&nbsp;directly we would=
 have the following: Hypotenuse =3D =E2=88=9A (a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2), that is,=
 Hypotenuse =3D =E2=88=9A (3=C2=B2 + 9=C2=B2) =3D 25 cm</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Exercise 2</strong>: We have a right triangle, the hypotenuse m=
easures 10 m and one leg measures 6 m=E2=80=A6 What is the value of the oth=
er leg (b)?
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;">
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>If we base it on the Pythagorean theorem (a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2=
) and solve for b to perform the calculations, we find that leg b =3D =E2=
=88=9A (a=C2=B2 + c=C2=B2)</li>
<li>The calculations would be: b =3D =E2=88=9A (6=C2=B2 + 10=C2=B2) =3D 8 c=
m the value of the leg.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
