<h3><strong>Frequently asked questions about the Pythagorean theorem =E2=80=
=93 FAQ</strong></h3>
<hr>
<p><strong>What is the Pythagorean theorem?</strong></p>
<p>The Pythagorean theorem is a mathematical formula used to find the lengt=
h of a side in a right triangle when the lengths of the other two sides are=
 known. The equation is a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2, where =E2=80=9Ca=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=9D are the legs and =E2=80=9Cc=E2=80=9D is the =
hypotenuse.</p>
<p><strong>What is the Pythagorean theorem used for?</strong></p>
<p>It is mainly used to solve problems with right triangles, such as findin=
g the length of an unknown side. It also has practical applications in cons=
truction, navigation, design, and many areas of physics and engineering.</p=
>
<p><strong>How is the Pythagorean theorem applied?</strong></p>
<p>It is applied by squaring the lengths of the two legs, adding them, and =
then taking the square root of the result to obtain the hypotenuse. If a le=
g is sought, the square of the other known leg is subtracted from the squar=
e of the hypotenuse and then the square root is taken.</p>
<p><strong>What is the formula of the Pythagorean theorem?</strong></p>
<p>The formula is a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2, where a and b represent th=
e legs of the right triangle and c represents the hypotenuse, which is the =
longest side and opposite the right angle.</p>
<p><strong>How do you know if a triangle is right using the Pythagorean the=
orem?</strong></p>
<p>If when applying the formula a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2 with the tria=
ngle=E2=80=99s measurements, the equality holds, then the triangle is right=
. If it does not hold, it is not.</p>
<p><strong>Does the Pythagorean theorem work on any triangle?</strong></p>
<p>No, it only works on right triangles, which have a 90-degree angle. If t=
he triangle is not right, the formula does not apply.</p>
<p><strong>How do you know which is the hypotenuse in a right triangle?</st=
rong></p>
<p>The hypotenuse is always the longest side of the right triangle and is o=
pposite the 90-degree angle. The other two sides are the legs.</p>
<p><strong>How to find the hypotenuse with the Pythagorean theorem?</strong=
></p>
<p>To find the hypotenuse, the lengths of the two legs are squared, added, =
and then the square root is applied to the result. This way, we obtain the =
length of the hypotenuse.</p>
<p><strong>How to find a leg with the Pythagorean theorem?</strong></p>
<p>To find an unknown leg, the hypotenuse is squared, the square of the oth=
er known leg is subtracted, and then the square root of the result is appli=
ed.</p>
<p><strong>Why is the Pythagorean theorem important?</strong></p>
<p>It is important because it is a fundamental tool in geometry and trigono=
metry. It allows solving problems related to distances and angles and has m=
ultiple applications in science, technology, engineering, and art.</p>
<p><strong>Who invented the Pythagorean theorem?</strong></p>
<p>Although the theorem is named after the Greek philosopher Pythagoras, wh=
o lived around the 6th century BC, there is evidence that earlier civilizat=
ions, such as the Babylonians and Egyptians, already used this relationship=
 between the sides of a right triangle.</p>
<p><strong>What is a Pythagorean triangle?</strong></p>
<p>It is a right triangle whose sides have lengths that are integers and sa=
tisfy a=C2=B2 + b=C2=B2 =3D c=C2=B2. A classic example is the triangle with=
